Ronald Martinez/Getty ImagesA new front opened up in Texas this week in the battle over how to conduct elections in the midst of a pandemic.
On Tuesday, Texas Attorney General Ken Paxton issued an interpretation of the state’s absentee-balloting provisions that would preclude those who are afraid of contracting COVID-19 from voting absentee by mail.
The language in Texas’ absentee balloting provision initially might read as being as restrictive as Paxton has interpreted it.
However, there’s another possible reading, one that has the backing of the state district judge in this case, Tim Sulak, and one that would greatly expand absentee voting rights for Texans.
Jennett—was, in fact, a Texas Supreme Court case.